4419static int tcp_try_rmem_schedule(struct sock *sk, struct sk_buff *skb,
4420 unsigned int size)
4421{
4422 if (atomic_read(&sk->sk_rmem_alloc) > sk->sk_rcvbuf ||
4423 !sk_rmem_schedule(sk, skb, size)) {
4424
4425 if (tcp_prune_queue(sk) < 0)
4426 return -1;
4427
4428 while (!sk_rmem_schedule(sk, skb, size)) {
4429 if (!tcp_prune_ofo_queue(sk))
4430 return -1;
4431 }
4432 }
4433 return 0;
4434}
4435
4436static void tcp_data_queue_ofo(struct sock *sk, struct sk_buff *skb)
4437{
4438 struct tcp_sock *tp = tcp_sk(sk);
4439 struct rb_node **p, *q, *parent;
4440 struct sk_buff *skb1;
4441 u32 seq, end_seq;
4442 bool fragstolen;
4443
4444 tcp_ecn_check_ce(tp, skb);
4445
4446 if (unlikely(tcp_try_rmem_schedule(sk, skb, skb->truesize))) {
4447 NET_INC_STATS(sock_net(sk), LINUX_MIB_TCPOFODROP);
4448 tcp_drop(sk, skb);
4449 return;
4450 }
4451
4452 /* Stash tstamp to avoid being stomped on by rbnode */
4453 if (TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->has_rxtstamp)
4454 TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->swtstamp = skb->tstamp;
4455
4456 /* Disable header prediction. */
4457 tp->pred_flags = 0;
4458 inet_csk_schedule_ack(sk);
4459
4460 NET_INC_STATS(sock_net(sk), LINUX_MIB_TCPOFOQUEUE);
4461 seq = TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->seq;
4462 end_seq = TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->end_seq;
4463 SOCK_DEBUG(sk, "out of order segment: rcv_next %X seq %X - %X\n",
4464 tp->rcv_nxt, seq, end_seq);
4465
4466 p = &tp->out_of_order_queue.rb_node;
4467 if (RB_EMPTY_ROOT(&tp->out_of_order_queue)) {
4468 /* Initial out of order segment, build 1 SACK. */
4469 if (tcp_is_sack(tp)) {
4470 tp->rx_opt.num_sacks = 1;
4471 tp->selective_acks[0].start_seq = seq;
4472 tp->selective_acks[0].end_seq = end_seq;
4473 }
4474 rb_link_node(&skb->rbnode, NULL, p);
4475 rb_insert_color(&skb->rbnode, &tp->out_of_order_queue);
4476 tp->ooo_last_skb = skb;
4477 goto end;
4478 }
4479
4480 /* In the typical case, we are adding an skb to the end of the list.
4481 * Use of ooo_last_skb avoids the O(Log(N)) rbtree lookup.
4482 */
4483 if (tcp_ooo_try_coalesce(sk, tp->ooo_last_skb,
4484 skb, &fragstolen)) {
4485coalesce_done:
4486 tcp_grow_window(sk, skb);
4487 kfree_skb_partial(skb, fragstolen);
4488 skb = NULL;
4489 goto add_sack;
4490 }
4491 /* Can avoid an rbtree lookup if we are adding skb after ooo_last_skb */
4492 if (!before(seq, TCP_SKB_CB(tp->ooo_last_skb)->end_seq)) {
4493 parent = &tp->ooo_last_skb->rbnode;
4494 p = &parent->rb_right;
4495 goto insert;
4496 }
4497
4498 /* Find place to insert this segment. Handle overlaps on the way. */
4499 parent = NULL;
4500 while (*p) {
4501 parent = *p;
4502 skb1 = rb_entry(parent, struct sk_buff, rbnode);
4503 if (before(seq, TCP_SKB_CB(skb1)->seq)) {
4504 p = &parent->rb_left;
4505 continue;
4506 }
4507 if (before(seq, TCP_SKB_CB(skb1)->end_seq)) {
4508 if (!after(end_seq, TCP_SKB_CB(skb1)->end_seq)) {
4509 /* All the bits are present. Drop. */
4510 NET_INC_STATS(sock_net(sk),
4511 LINUX_MIB_TCPOFOMERGE);
4512 tcp_drop(sk, skb);
4513 skb = NULL;
4514 tcp_dsack_set(sk, seq, end_seq);
4515 goto add_sack;
4516 }
4517 if (after(seq, TCP_SKB_CB(skb1)->seq)) {
4518 /* Partial overlap. */
4519 tcp_dsack_set(sk, seq, TCP_SKB_CB(skb1)->end_seq);
4520 } else {
4521 /* skb's seq == skb1's seq and skb covers skb1.
4522 * Replace skb1 with skb.
4523 */
4524 rb_replace_node(&skb1->rbnode, &skb->rbnode,
4525 &tp->out_of_order_queue);
4526 tcp_dsack_extend(sk,
4527 TCP_SKB_CB(skb1)->seq,
4528 TCP_SKB_CB(skb1)->end_seq);
4529 NET_INC_STATS(sock_net(sk),
4530 LINUX_MIB_TCPOFOMERGE);
4531 tcp_drop(sk, skb1);
4532 goto merge_right;
4533 }
4534 } else if (tcp_ooo_try_coalesce(sk, skb1,
4535 skb, &fragstolen)) {
4536 goto coalesce_done;
4537 }
4538 p = &parent->rb_right;
4539 }
4540insert:
4541 /* Insert segment into RB tree. */
4542 rb_link_node(&skb->rbnode, parent, p);
4543 rb_insert_color(&skb->rbnode, &tp->out_of_order_queue);
4544
4545merge_right:
4546 /* Remove other segments covered by skb. */
4547 while ((q = rb_next(&skb->rbnode)) != NULL) {
4548 skb1 = rb_entry(q, struct sk_buff, rbnode);
4549
4550 if (!after(end_seq, TCP_SKB_CB(skb1)->seq))
4551 break;
4552 if (before(end_seq, TCP_SKB_CB(skb1)->end_seq)) {
4553 tcp_dsack_extend(sk, TCP_SKB_CB(skb1)->seq,
4554 end_seq);
4555 break;
4556 }
4557 rb_erase(&skb1->rbnode, &tp->out_of_order_queue);
4558 tcp_dsack_extend(sk, TCP_SKB_CB(skb1)->seq,
4559 TCP_SKB_CB(skb1)->end_seq);
4560 NET_INC_STATS(sock_net(sk), LINUX_MIB_TCPOFOMERGE);
4561 tcp_drop(sk, skb1);
4562 }
4563 /* If there is no skb after us, we are the last_skb ! */
4564 if (!q)
4565 tp->ooo_last_skb = skb;
4566
4567add_sack:
4568 if (tcp_is_sack(tp))
4569 tcp_sack_new_ofo_skb(sk, seq, end_seq);
4570end:
4571 if (skb) {
4572 tcp_grow_window(sk, skb);
4573 skb_condense(skb);
4574 skb_set_owner_r(skb, sk);
4575 }
4576}
4577
4578static int __must_check tcp_queue_rcv(struct sock *sk, struct sk_buff *skb, int hdrlen,
4579 bool *fragstolen)
4580{
4581 int eaten;
4582 struct sk_buff *tail = skb_peek_tail(&sk->sk_receive_queue);
4583
4584 __skb_pull(skb, hdrlen);
4585 eaten = (tail &&
4586 tcp_try_coalesce(sk, RCV_QUEUE, tail,
4587 skb, fragstolen)) ? 1 : 0;
4588 tcp_rcv_nxt_update(tcp_sk(sk), TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->end_seq);
4589 if (!eaten) {
4590 __skb_queue_tail(&sk->sk_receive_queue, skb);
4591 skb_set_owner_r(skb, sk);
4592 }
4593 return eaten;
4594}
4595
4596int tcp_send_rcvq(struct sock *sk, struct msghdr *msg, size_t size)
4597{
4598 struct sk_buff *skb;
4599 int err = -ENOMEM;
4600 int data_len = 0;
4601 bool fragstolen;
4602
4603 if (size == 0)
4604 return 0;
4605
4606 if (size > PAGE_SIZE) {
4607 int npages = min_t(size_t, size >> PAGE_SHIFT, MAX_SKB_FRAGS);
4608
4609 data_len = npages << PAGE_SHIFT;
4610 size = data_len + (size & ~PAGE_MASK);
4611 }
4612 skb = alloc_skb_with_frags(size - data_len, data_len,
4613 PAGE_ALLOC_COSTLY_ORDER,
4614 &err, sk->sk_allocation);
4615 if (!skb)
4616 goto err;
4617
4618 skb_put(skb, size - data_len);
4619 skb->data_len = data_len;
4620 skb->len = size;
4621
4622 if (tcp_try_rmem_schedule(sk, skb, skb->truesize))
4623 goto err_free;
4624
4625 err = skb_copy_datagram_from_iter(skb, 0, &msg->msg_iter, size);
4626 if (err)
4627 goto err_free;
4628
4629 TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->seq = tcp_sk(sk)->rcv_nxt;
4630 TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->end_seq = TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->seq + size;
4631 TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->ack_seq = tcp_sk(sk)->snd_una - 1;
4632
4633 if (tcp_queue_rcv(sk, skb, 0, &fragstolen)) {
4634 WARN_ON_ONCE(fragstolen); /* should not happen */
4635 __kfree_skb(skb);
4636 }
4637 return size;
4638
4639err_free:
4640 kfree_skb(skb);
4641err:
4642 return err;
4643
4644}
4645
4646static void tcp_data_queue(struct sock *sk, struct sk_buff *skb)
4647{
4648 struct tcp_sock *tp = tcp_sk(sk);
4649 bool fragstolen;
4650 int eaten;
4651
4652 if (TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->seq == TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->end_seq) {
4653 __kfree_skb(skb);
4654 return;
4655 }
4656 skb_dst_drop(skb);
4657 __skb_pull(skb, tcp_hdr(skb)->doff * 4);
4658
4659 tcp_ecn_accept_cwr(tp, skb);
4660
4661 tp->rx_opt.dsack = 0;
4662
4663 /* Queue data for delivery to the user.
4664 * Packets in sequence go to the receive queue.
4665 * Out of sequence packets to the out_of_order_queue.
4666 */
4667 if (TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->seq == tp->rcv_nxt) {
4668 if (tcp_receive_window(tp) == 0)
4669 goto out_of_window;
4670
4671 /* Ok. In sequence. In window. */
4672queue_and_out:
4673 if (skb_queue_len(&sk->sk_receive_queue) == 0)
4674 sk_forced_mem_schedule(sk, skb->truesize);
4675 else if (tcp_try_rmem_schedule(sk, skb, skb->truesize))
4676 goto drop;
4677
4678 eaten = tcp_queue_rcv(sk, skb, 0, &fragstolen);
4679 tcp_rcv_nxt_update(tp, TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->end_seq);
4680 if (skb->len)
4681 tcp_event_data_recv(sk, skb);
4682 if (TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->tcp_flags & TCPHDR_FIN)
4683 tcp_fin(sk);
4684
4685 if (!RB_EMPTY_ROOT(&tp->out_of_order_queue)) {
4686 tcp_ofo_queue(sk);
4687
4688 /* RFC2581. 4.2. SHOULD send immediate ACK, when
4689 * gap in queue is filled.
4690 */
4691 if (RB_EMPTY_ROOT(&tp->out_of_order_queue))
4692 inet_csk(sk)->icsk_ack.pingpong = 0;
4693 }
4694
4695 if (tp->rx_opt.num_sacks)
4696 tcp_sack_remove(tp);
4697
4698 tcp_fast_path_check(sk);
4699
4700 if (eaten > 0)
4701 kfree_skb_partial(skb, fragstolen);
4702 if (!sock_flag(sk, SOCK_DEAD))
4703 sk->sk_data_ready(sk);
4704 return;
4705 }
4706
4707 if (!after(TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->end_seq, tp->rcv_nxt)) {
4708 /* A retransmit, 2nd most common case. Force an immediate ack. */
4709 NET_INC_STATS(sock_net(sk), LINUX_MIB_DELAYEDACKLOST);
4710 tcp_dsack_set(sk, TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->seq, TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->end_seq);
4711
4712out_of_window:
4713 tcp_enter_quickack_mode(sk);
4714 inet_csk_schedule_ack(sk);
4715drop:
4716 tcp_drop(sk, skb);
4717 return;
4718 }
4719
4720 /* Out of window. F.e. zero window probe. */
4721 if (!before(TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->seq, tp->rcv_nxt + tcp_receive_window(tp)))
4722 goto out_of_window;
4723
4724 tcp_enter_quickack_mode(sk);
4725
4726 if (before(TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->seq, tp->rcv_nxt)) {
4727 /* Partial packet, seq < rcv_next < end_seq */
4728 SOCK_DEBUG(sk, "partial packet: rcv_next %X seq %X - %X\n",
4729 tp->rcv_nxt, TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->seq,
4730 TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->end_seq);
4731
4732 tcp_dsack_set(sk, TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->seq, tp->rcv_nxt);
4733
4734 /* If window is closed, drop tail of packet. But after
4735 * remembering D-SACK for its head made in previous line.
4736 */
4737 if (!tcp_receive_window(tp))
4738 goto out_of_window;
4739 goto queue_and_out;
4740 }
4741
4742 tcp_data_queue_ofo(sk, skb);
4743}
4744
4745static struct sk_buff *tcp_skb_next(struct sk_buff *skb, struct sk_buff_head *list)
4746{
4747 if (list)
4748 return !skb_queue_is_last(list, skb) ? skb->next : NULL;
4749
4750 return rb_entry_safe(rb_next(&skb->rbnode), struct sk_buff, rbnode);
4751}
4752
4753static struct sk_buff *tcp_collapse_one(struct sock *sk, struct sk_buff *skb,
4754 struct sk_buff_head *list,
4755 struct rb_root *root)
4756{
4757 struct sk_buff *next = tcp_skb_next(skb, list);
4758
4759 if (list)
4760 __skb_unlink(skb, list);
4761 else
4762 rb_erase(&skb->rbnode, root);
4763
4764 __kfree_skb(skb);
4765 NET_INC_STATS(sock_net(sk), LINUX_MIB_TCPRCVCOLLAPSED);
4766
4767 return next;
4768}
4769
4770/* Insert skb into rb tree, ordered by TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->seq */
4771static void tcp_rbtree_insert(struct rb_root *root, struct sk_buff *skb)
4772{
4773 struct rb_node **p = &root->rb_node;
4774 struct rb_node *parent = NULL;
4775 struct sk_buff *skb1;
4776
4777 while (*p) {
4778 parent = *p;
4779 skb1 = rb_entry(parent, struct sk_buff, rbnode);
4780 if (before(TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->seq, TCP_SKB_CB(skb1)->seq))
4781 p = &parent->rb_left;
4782 else
4783 p = &parent->rb_right;
4784 }
4785 rb_link_node(&skb->rbnode, parent, p);
4786 rb_insert_color(&skb->rbnode, root);
4787}
4788
4789/* Collapse contiguous sequence of skbs head..tail with
4790 * sequence numbers start..end.
4791 *
4792 * If tail is NULL, this means until the end of the queue.
4793 *
4794 * Segments with FIN/SYN are not collapsed (only because this
4795 * simplifies code)
4796 */
4797static void
4798tcp_collapse(struct sock *sk, struct sk_buff_head *list, struct rb_root *root,
4799 struct sk_buff *head, struct sk_buff *tail, u32 start, u32 end)
4800{
4801 struct sk_buff *skb = head, *n;
4802 struct sk_buff_head tmp;
4803 bool end_of_skbs;
4804
4805 /* First, check that queue is collapsible and find
4806 * the point where collapsing can be useful.
4807 */
4808restart:
4809 for (end_of_skbs = true; skb != NULL && skb != tail; skb = n) {
4810 n = tcp_skb_next(skb, list);
4811
4812 /* No new bits? It is possible on ofo queue. */
4813 if (!before(start, TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->end_seq)) {
4814 skb = tcp_collapse_one(sk, skb, list, root);
4815 if (!skb)
4816 break;
4817 goto restart;
4818 }
4819
4820 /* The first skb to collapse is:
4821 * - not SYN/FIN and
4822 * - bloated or contains data before "start" or
4823 * overlaps to the next one.
4824 */
4825 if (!(TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->tcp_flags & (TCPHDR_SYN | TCPHDR_FIN)) &&
4826 (tcp_win_from_space(skb->truesize) > skb->len ||
4827 before(TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->seq, start))) {
4828 end_of_skbs = false;
4829 break;
4830 }
4831
4832 if (n && n != tail &&
4833 TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->end_seq != TCP_SKB_CB(n)->seq) {
4834 end_of_skbs = false;
4835 break;
4836 }
4837
4838 /* Decided to skip this, advance start seq. */
4839 start = TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->end_seq;
4840 }
4841 if (end_of_skbs ||
4842 (TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->tcp_flags & (TCPHDR_SYN | TCPHDR_FIN)))
4843 return;
4844
4845 __skb_queue_head_init(&tmp);
4846
4847 while (before(start, end)) {
4848 int copy = min_t(int, SKB_MAX_ORDER(0, 0), end - start);
4849 struct sk_buff *nskb;
4850
4851 nskb = alloc_skb(copy, GFP_ATOMIC);
4852 if (!nskb)
4853 break;
4854
4855 memcpy(nskb->cb, skb->cb, sizeof(skb->cb));
4856 TCP_SKB_CB(nskb)->seq = TCP_SKB_CB(nskb)->end_seq = start;
4857 if (list)
4858 __skb_queue_before(list, skb, nskb);
4859 else
4860 __skb_queue_tail(&tmp, nskb); /* defer rbtree insertion */
4861 skb_set_owner_r(nskb, sk);
4862
4863 /* Copy data, releasing collapsed skbs. */
4864 while (copy > 0) {
4865 int offset = start - TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->seq;
4866 int size = TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->end_seq - start;
4867
4868 BUG_ON(offset < 0);
4869 if (size > 0) {
4870 size = min(copy, size);
4871 if (skb_copy_bits(skb, offset, skb_put(nskb, size), size))
4872 BUG();
4873 TCP_SKB_CB(nskb)->end_seq += size;
4874 copy -= size;
4875 start += size;
4876 }
4877 if (!before(start, TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->end_seq)) {
4878 skb = tcp_collapse_one(sk, skb, list, root);
4879 if (!skb ||
4880 skb == tail ||
4881 (TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->tcp_flags & (TCPHDR_SYN | TCPHDR_FIN)))
4882 goto end;
4883 }
4884 }
4885 }
4886end:
4887 skb_queue_walk_safe(&tmp, skb, n)
4888 tcp_rbtree_insert(root, skb);
4889}
4890
4891/* Collapse ofo queue. Algorithm: select contiguous sequence of skbs
4892 * and tcp_collapse() them until all the queue is collapsed.
4893 */
4894static void tcp_collapse_ofo_queue(struct sock *sk)
4895{
4896 struct tcp_sock *tp = tcp_sk(sk);
4897 u32 range_truesize, sum_tiny = 0;
4898 struct sk_buff *skb, *head;
4899 struct rb_node *p;
4900 u32 start, end;
4901
4902 p = rb_first(&tp->out_of_order_queue);
4903 skb = rb_entry_safe(p, struct sk_buff, rbnode);
4904new_range:
4905 if (!skb) {
4906 p = rb_last(&tp->out_of_order_queue);
4907 /* Note: This is possible p is NULL here. We do not
4908 * use rb_entry_safe(), as ooo_last_skb is valid only
4909 * if rbtree is not empty.
4910 */
4911 tp->ooo_last_skb = rb_entry(p, struct sk_buff, rbnode);
4912 return;
4913 }
4914 start = TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->seq;
4915 end = TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->end_seq;
4916 range_truesize = skb->truesize;
4917
4918 for (head = skb;;) {
4919 skb = tcp_skb_next(skb, NULL);
4920
4921 /* Range is terminated when we see a gap or when
4922 * we are at the queue end.
4923 */
4924 if (!skb ||
4925 after(TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->seq, end) ||
4926 before(TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->end_seq, start)) {
4927 /* Do not attempt collapsing tiny skbs */
4928 if (range_truesize != head->truesize ||
4929 end - start >= SKB_WITH_OVERHEAD(SK_MEM_QUANTUM)) {
4930 tcp_collapse(sk, NULL, &tp->out_of_order_queue,
4931 head, skb, start, end);
4932 } else {
4933 sum_tiny += range_truesize;
4934 if (sum_tiny > sk->sk_rcvbuf >> 3)
4935 return;
4936 }
4937 goto new_range;
4938 }
4939
4940 range_truesize += skb->truesize;
4941 if (unlikely(before(TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->seq, start)))
4942 start = TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->seq;
4943 if (after(TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->end_seq, end))
4944 end = TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->end_seq;
4945 }
4946}
4947
4948/*
4949 * Clean the out-of-order queue to make room.
4950 * We drop high sequences packets to :
4951 * 1) Let a chance for holes to be filled.
4952 * 2) not add too big latencies if thousands of packets sit there.
4953 * (But if application shrinks SO_RCVBUF, we could still end up
4954 * freeing whole queue here)
4955 * 3) Drop at least 12.5 % of sk_rcvbuf to avoid malicious attacks.
4956 *
4957 * Return true if queue has shrunk.
4958 */
4959static bool tcp_prune_ofo_queue(struct sock *sk)
4960{
4961 struct tcp_sock *tp = tcp_sk(sk);
4962 struct rb_node *node, *prev;
4963 int goal;
4964
4965 if (RB_EMPTY_ROOT(&tp->out_of_order_queue))
4966 return false;
4967
4968 NET_INC_STATS(sock_net(sk), LINUX_MIB_OFOPRUNED);
4969 goal = sk->sk_rcvbuf >> 3;
4970 node = &tp->ooo_last_skb->rbnode;
4971 do {
4972 prev = rb_prev(node);
4973 rb_erase(node, &tp->out_of_order_queue);
4974 goal -= rb_to_skb(node)->truesize;
4975 tcp_drop(sk, rb_entry(node, struct sk_buff, rbnode));
4976 if (!prev || goal <= 0) {
4977 sk_mem_reclaim(sk);
4978 if (atomic_read(&sk->sk_rmem_alloc) <= sk->sk_rcvbuf &&
4979 !tcp_under_memory_pressure(sk))
4980 break;
4981 goal = sk->sk_rcvbuf >> 3;
4982 }
4983 node = prev;
4984 } while (node);
4985 tp->ooo_last_skb = rb_entry(prev, struct sk_buff, rbnode);
4986
4987 /* Reset SACK state. A conforming SACK implementation will
4988 * do the same at a timeout based retransmit. When a connection
4989 * is in a sad state like this, we care only about integrity
4990 * of the connection not performance.
4991 */
4992 if (tp->rx_opt.sack_ok)
4993 tcp_sack_reset(&tp->rx_opt);
4994 return true;
4995}
4996
4997/* Reduce allocated memory if we can, trying to get
4998 * the socket within its memory limits again.
4999 *
5000 * Return less than zero if we should start dropping frames
5001 * until the socket owning process reads some of the data
5002 * to stabilize the situation.
5003 */
5004static int tcp_prune_queue(struct sock *sk)
5005{
5006 struct tcp_sock *tp = tcp_sk(sk);
5007
5008 SOCK_DEBUG(sk, "prune_queue: c=%x\n", tp->copied_seq);
5009
5010 NET_INC_STATS(sock_net(sk), LINUX_MIB_PRUNECALLED);
5011
5012 if (atomic_read(&sk->sk_rmem_alloc) >= sk->sk_rcvbuf)
5013 tcp_clamp_window(sk);
5014 else if (tcp_under_memory_pressure(sk))
5015 tp->rcv_ssthresh = min(tp->rcv_ssthresh, 4U * tp->advmss);
5016
5017 if (atomic_read(&sk->sk_rmem_alloc) <= sk->sk_rcvbuf)
5018 return 0;
5019
5020 tcp_collapse_ofo_queue(sk);
5021 if (!skb_queue_empty(&sk->sk_receive_queue))
5022 tcp_collapse(sk, &sk->sk_receive_queue, NULL,
5023 skb_peek(&sk->sk_receive_queue),
5024 NULL,
5025 tp->copied_seq, tp->rcv_nxt);
5026 sk_mem_reclaim(sk);
5027
5028 if (atomic_read(&sk->sk_rmem_alloc) <= sk->sk_rcvbuf)
5029 return 0;
5030
5031 /* Collapsing did not help, destructive actions follow.
5032 * This must not ever occur. */
5033
5034 tcp_prune_ofo_queue(sk);
5035
5036 if (atomic_read(&sk->sk_rmem_alloc) <= sk->sk_rcvbuf)
5037 return 0;
5038
5039 /* If we are really being abused, tell the caller to silently
5040 * drop receive data on the floor. It will get retransmitted
5041 * and hopefully then we'll have sufficient space.
5042 */
5043 NET_INC_STATS(sock_net(sk), LINUX_MIB_RCVPRUNED);
5044
5045 /* Massive buffer overcommit. */
5046 tp->pred_flags = 0;
5047 return -1;
5048}
5049
5050static bool tcp_should_expand_sndbuf(const struct sock *sk)
5051{
5052 const struct tcp_sock *tp = tcp_sk(sk);
5053
5054 /* If the user specified a specific send buffer setting, do
5055 * not modify it.
5056 */
5057 if (sk->sk_userlocks & SOCK_SNDBUF_LOCK)
5058 return false;
5059
5060 /* If we are under global TCP memory pressure, do not expand. */
5061 if (tcp_under_memory_pressure(sk))
5062 return false;
5063
5064 /* If we are under soft global TCP memory pressure, do not expand. */
5065 if (sk_memory_allocated(sk) >= sk_prot_mem_limits(sk, 0))
5066 return false;
5067
5068 /* If we filled the congestion window, do not expand. */
5069 if (tcp_packets_in_flight(tp) >= tp->snd_cwnd)
5070 return false;
5071
5072 return true;
5073}
5074
5075/* When incoming ACK allowed to free some skb from write_queue,
5076 * we remember this event in flag SOCK_QUEUE_SHRUNK and wake up socket
5077 * on the exit from tcp input handler.
5078 *
5079 * PROBLEM: sndbuf expansion does not work well with largesend.
5080 */
5081static void tcp_new_space(struct sock *sk)
5082{
5083 struct tcp_sock *tp = tcp_sk(sk);
5084
5085 if (tcp_should_expand_sndbuf(sk)) {
5086 tcp_sndbuf_expand(sk);
5087 tp->snd_cwnd_stamp = tcp_jiffies32;
5088 }
5089
5090 sk->sk_write_space(sk);
5091}
5092
5093static void tcp_check_space(struct sock *sk)
5094{
5095 if (sock_flag(sk, SOCK_QUEUE_SHRUNK)) {
5096 sock_reset_flag(sk, SOCK_QUEUE_SHRUNK);
5097 /* pairs with tcp_poll() */
5098 smp_mb();
5099 if (sk->sk_socket &&
5100 test_bit(SOCK_NOSPACE, &sk->sk_socket->flags)) {
5101 tcp_new_space(sk);
5102 if (!test_bit(SOCK_NOSPACE, &sk->sk_socket->flags))
5103 tcp_chrono_stop(sk, TCP_CHRONO_SNDBUF_LIMITED);
5104 }
5105 }
5106}
5107
5108static inline void tcp_data_snd_check(struct sock *sk)
5109{
5110 tcp_push_pending_frames(sk);
5111 tcp_check_space(sk);
5112}

5114/*
5115 * Check if sending an ack is needed.
5116 */
5117static void __tcp_ack_snd_check(struct sock *sk, int ofo_possible)
5118{
5119 struct tcp_sock *tp = tcp_sk(sk);
5120
5121 /* More than one full frame received... */
5122 if (((tp->rcv_nxt - tp->rcv_wup) > inet_csk(sk)->icsk_ack.rcv_mss &&
5123 /* ... and right edge of window advances far enough.
5124 * (tcp_recvmsg() will send ACK otherwise). Or...
5125 */
5126 __tcp_select_window(sk) >= tp->rcv_wnd) ||
5127 /* We ACK each frame or... */
5128 tcp_in_quickack_mode(sk) ||
5129 /* We have out of order data. */
5130 (ofo_possible && !RB_EMPTY_ROOT(&tp->out_of_order_queue))) {
5131 /* Then ack it now */
5132 tcp_send_ack(sk);
5133 } else {
5134 /* Else, send delayed ack. */
5135 tcp_send_delayed_ack(sk);
5136 }
5137}
5138
5139static inline void tcp_ack_snd_check(struct sock *sk)
5140{
5141 if (!inet_csk_ack_scheduled(sk)) {
5142 /* We sent a data segment already. */
5143 return;
5144 }
5145 __tcp_ack_snd_check(sk, 1);
5146}
5147
5148/*
5149 * This routine is only called when we have urgent data
5150 * signaled. Its the 'slow' part of tcp_urg. It could be
5151 * moved inline now as tcp_urg is only called from one
5152 * place. We handle URGent data wrong. We have to - as
5153 * BSD still doesn't use the correction from RFC961.
5154 * For 1003.1g we should support a new option TCP_STDURG to permit
5155 * either form (or just set the sysctl tcp_stdurg).
5156 */
5157
5158static void tcp_check_urg(struct sock *sk, const struct tcphdr *th)
5159{
5160 struct tcp_sock *tp = tcp_sk(sk);
5161 u32 ptr = ntohs(th->urg_ptr);
5162
5163 if (ptr && !sysctl_tcp_stdurg)
5164 ptr--;
5165 ptr += ntohl(th->seq);
5166
5167 /* Ignore urgent data that we've already seen and read. */
5168 if (after(tp->copied_seq, ptr))
5169 return;
5170
5171 /* Do not replay urg ptr.
5172 *
5173 * NOTE: interesting situation not covered by specs.
5174 * Misbehaving sender may send urg ptr, pointing to segment,
5175 * which we already have in ofo queue. We are not able to fetch
5176 * such data and will stay in TCP_URG_NOTYET until will be eaten
5177 * by recvmsg(). Seems, we are not obliged to handle such wicked
5178 * situations. But it is worth to think about possibility of some
5179 * DoSes using some hypothetical application level deadlock.
5180 */
5181 if (before(ptr, tp->rcv_nxt))
5182 return;
5183
5184 /* Do we already have a newer (or duplicate) urgent pointer? */
5185 if (tp->urg_data && !after(ptr, tp->urg_seq))
5186 return;
5187
5188 /* Tell the world about our new urgent pointer. */
5189 sk_send_sigurg(sk);
5190
5191 /* We may be adding urgent data when the last byte read was
5192 * urgent. To do this requires some care. We cannot just ignore
5193 * tp->copied_seq since we would read the last urgent byte again
5194 * as data, nor can we alter copied_seq until this data arrives
5195 * or we break the semantics of SIOCATMARK (and thus sockatmark())
5196 *
5197 * NOTE. Double Dutch. Rendering to plain English: author of comment
5198 * above did something sort of send("A", MSG_OOB); send("B", MSG_OOB);
5199 * and expect that both A and B disappear from stream. This is _wrong_.
5200 * Though this happens in BSD with high probability, this is occasional.
5201 * Any application relying on this is buggy. Note also, that fix "works"
5202 * only in this artificial test. Insert some normal data between A and B and we will
5203 * decline of BSD again. Verdict: it is better to remove to trap
5204 * buggy users.
5205 */
5206 if (tp->urg_seq == tp->copied_seq && tp->urg_data &&
5207 !sock_flag(sk, SOCK_URGINLINE) && tp->copied_seq != tp->rcv_nxt) {
5208 struct sk_buff *skb = skb_peek(&sk->sk_receive_queue);
5209 tp->copied_seq++;
5210 if (skb && !before(tp->copied_seq, TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->end_seq)) {
5211 __skb_unlink(skb, &sk->sk_receive_queue);
5212 __kfree_skb(skb);
5213 }
5214 }
5215
5216 tp->urg_data = TCP_URG_NOTYET;
5217 tp->urg_seq = ptr;
5218
5219 /* Disable header prediction. */
5220 tp->pred_flags = 0;
5221}
5222
5223/* This is the 'fast' part of urgent handling. */
5224static void tcp_urg(struct sock *sk, struct sk_buff *skb, const struct tcphdr *th)
5225{
5226 struct tcp_sock *tp = tcp_sk(sk);
5227
5228 /* Check if we get a new urgent pointer - normally not. */
5229 if (th->urg)
5230 tcp_check_urg(sk, th);
5231
5232 /* Do we wait for any urgent data? - normally not... */
5233 if (tp->urg_data == TCP_URG_NOTYET) {
5234 u32 ptr = tp->urg_seq - ntohl(th->seq) + (th->doff * 4) -
5235 th->syn;
5236
5237 /* Is the urgent pointer pointing into this packet? */
5238 if (ptr < skb->len) {
5239 u8 tmp;
5240 if (skb_copy_bits(skb, ptr, &tmp, 1))
5241 BUG();
5242 tp->urg_data = TCP_URG_VALID | tmp;
5243 if (!sock_flag(sk, SOCK_DEAD))
5244 sk->sk_data_ready(sk);
5245 }
5246 }
5247}
5248
5249/* Accept RST for rcv_nxt - 1 after a FIN.
5250 * When tcp connections are abruptly terminated from Mac OSX (via ^C), a
5251 * FIN is sent followed by a RST packet. The RST is sent with the same
5252 * sequence number as the FIN, and thus according to RFC 5961 a challenge
5253 * ACK should be sent. However, Mac OSX rate limits replies to challenge
5254 * ACKs on the closed socket. In addition middleboxes can drop either the
5255 * challenge ACK or a subsequent RST.
5256 */
5257static bool tcp_reset_check(const struct sock *sk, const struct sk_buff *skb)
5258{
5259 struct tcp_sock *tp = tcp_sk(sk);
5260
5261 return unlikely(TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->seq == (tp->rcv_nxt - 1) &&
5262 (1 << sk->sk_state) & (TCPF_CLOSE_WAIT | TCPF_LAST_ACK |
5263 TCPF_CLOSING));
5264}
5265
5266/* Does PAWS and seqno based validation of an incoming segment, flags will
5267 * play significant role here.
5268 */
5269static bool tcp_validate_incoming(struct sock *sk, struct sk_buff *skb,
5270 const struct tcphdr *th, int syn_inerr)
5271{
5272 struct tcp_sock *tp = tcp_sk(sk);
5273 bool rst_seq_match = false;
5274
5275 /* RFC1323: H1. Apply PAWS check first. */
5276 if (tcp_fast_parse_options(sock_net(sk), skb, th, tp) &&
5277 tp->rx_opt.saw_tstamp &&
5278 tcp_paws_discard(sk, skb)) {
5279 if (!th->rst) {
5280 NET_INC_STATS(sock_net(sk), LINUX_MIB_PAWSESTABREJECTED);
5281 if (!tcp_oow_rate_limited(sock_net(sk), skb,
5282 LINUX_MIB_TCPACKSKIPPEDPAWS,
5283 &tp->last_oow_ack_time))
5284 tcp_send_dupack(sk, skb);
5285 goto discard;
5286 }
5287 /* Reset is accepted even if it did not pass PAWS. */
5288 }
5289
5290 /* Step 1: check sequence number */
5291 if (!tcp_sequence(tp, TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->seq, TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->end_seq)) {
5292 /* RFC793, page 37: "In all states except SYN-SENT, all reset
5293 * (RST) segments are validated by checking their SEQ-fields."
5294 * And page 69: "If an incoming segment is not acceptable,
5295 * an acknowledgment should be sent in reply (unless the RST
5296 * bit is set, if so drop the segment and return)".
5297 */
5298 if (!th->rst) {
5299 if (th->syn)
5300 goto syn_challenge;
5301 if (!tcp_oow_rate_limited(sock_net(sk), skb,
5302 LINUX_MIB_TCPACKSKIPPEDSEQ,
5303 &tp->last_oow_ack_time))
5304 tcp_send_dupack(sk, skb);
5305 } else if (tcp_reset_check(sk, skb)) {
5306 tcp_reset(sk);
5307 }
5308 goto discard;
5309 }
5310
5311 /* Step 2: check RST bit */
5312 if (th->rst) {
5313 /* RFC 5961 3.2 (extend to match against (RCV.NXT - 1) after a
5314 * FIN and SACK too if available):
5315 * If seq num matches RCV.NXT or (RCV.NXT - 1) after a FIN, or
5316 * the right-most SACK block,
5317 * then
5318 * RESET the connection
5319 * else
5320 * Send a challenge ACK
5321 */
5322 if (TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->seq == tp->rcv_nxt ||
5323 tcp_reset_check(sk, skb)) {
5324 rst_seq_match = true;
5325 } else if (tcp_is_sack(tp) && tp->rx_opt.num_sacks > 0) {
5326 struct tcp_sack_block *sp = &tp->selective_acks[0];
5327 int max_sack = sp[0].end_seq;
5328 int this_sack;
5329
5330 for (this_sack = 1; this_sack < tp->rx_opt.num_sacks;
5331 ++this_sack) {
5332 max_sack = after(sp[this_sack].end_seq,
5333 max_sack) ?
5334 sp[this_sack].end_seq : max_sack;
5335 }
5336
5337 if (TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->seq == max_sack)
5338 rst_seq_match = true;
5339 }
5340
5341 if (rst_seq_match)
5342 tcp_reset(sk);
5343 else {
5344 /* Disable TFO if RST is out-of-order
5345 * and no data has been received
5346 * for current active TFO socket
5347 */
5348 if (tp->syn_fastopen && !tp->data_segs_in &&
5349 sk->sk_state == TCP_ESTABLISHED)
5350 tcp_fastopen_active_disable(sk);
5351 tcp_send_challenge_ack(sk, skb);
5352 }
5353 goto discard;
5354 }
5355
5356 /* step 3: check security and precedence [ignored] */
5357
5358 /* step 4: Check for a SYN
5359 * RFC 5961 4.2 : Send a challenge ack
5360 */
5361 if (th->syn) {
5362syn_challenge:
5363 if (syn_inerr)
5364 TCP_INC_STATS(sock_net(sk), TCP_MIB_INERRS);
5365 NET_INC_STATS(sock_net(sk), LINUX_MIB_TCPSYNCHALLENGE);
5366 tcp_send_challenge_ack(sk, skb);
5367 goto discard;
5368 }
5369
5370 return true;
5371
5372discard:
5373 tcp_drop(sk, skb);
5374 return false;
5375}
5376
5377/*
5378 * TCP receive function for the ESTABLISHED state.
5379 *
5380 * It is split into a fast path and a slow path. The fast path is
5381 * disabled when:
5382 * - A zero window was announced from us - zero window probing
5383 * is only handled properly in the slow path.
5384 * - Out of order segments arrived.
5385 * - Urgent data is expected.
5386 * - There is no buffer space left
5387 * - Unexpected TCP flags/window values/header lengths are received
5388 * (detected by checking the TCP header against pred_flags)
5389 * - Data is sent in both directions. Fast path only supports pure senders
5390 * or pure receivers (this means either the sequence number or the ack
5391 * value must stay constant)
5392 * - Unexpected TCP option.
5393 *
5394 * When these conditions are not satisfied it drops into a standard
5395 * receive procedure patterned after RFC793 to handle all cases.
5396 * The first three cases are guaranteed by proper pred_flags setting,
5397 * the rest is checked inline. Fast processing is turned on in
5398 * tcp_data_queue when everything is OK.
5399 */
5400void tcp_rcv_established(struct sock *sk, struct sk_buff *skb,
5401 const struct tcphdr *th)
5402{
5403 unsigned int len = skb->len;
5404 struct tcp_sock *tp = tcp_sk(sk);
5405
5406 tcp_mstamp_refresh(tp);
5407 if (unlikely(!sk->sk_rx_dst))
5408 inet_csk(sk)->icsk_af_ops->sk_rx_dst_set(sk, skb);
5409 /*
5410 * Header prediction.
5411 * The code loosely follows the one in the famous
5412 * "30 instruction TCP receive" Van Jacobson mail.
5413 *
5414 * Van's trick is to deposit buffers into socket queue
5415 * on a device interrupt, to call tcp_recv function
5416 * on the receive process context and checksum and copy
5417 * the buffer to user space. smart...
5418 *
5419 * Our current scheme is not silly either but we take the
5420 * extra cost of the net_bh soft interrupt processing...
5421 * We do checksum and copy also but from device to kernel.
5422 */
5423
5424 tp->rx_opt.saw_tstamp = 0;
5425
5426 /* pred_flags is 0xS?10 << 16 + snd_wnd
5427 * if header_prediction is to be made
5428 * 'S' will always be tp->tcp_header_len >> 2
5429 * '?' will be 0 for the fast path, otherwise pred_flags is 0 to
5430 * turn it off (when there are holes in the receive
5431 * space for instance)
5432 * PSH flag is ignored.
5433 */
5434
5435 if ((tcp_flag_word(th) & TCP_HP_BITS) == tp->pred_flags &&
5436 TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->seq == tp->rcv_nxt &&
5437 !after(TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->ack_seq, tp->snd_nxt)) {
5438 int tcp_header_len = tp->tcp_header_len;
5439
5440 /* Timestamp header prediction: tcp_header_len
5441 * is automatically equal to th->doff*4 due to pred_flags
5442 * match.
5443 */
5444
5445 /* Check timestamp */
5446 if (tcp_header_len == sizeof(struct tcphdr) + TCPOLEN_TSTAMP_ALIGNED) {
5447 /* No? Slow path! */
5448 if (!tcp_parse_aligned_timestamp(tp, th))
5449 goto slow_path;
5450
5451 /* If PAWS failed, check it more carefully in slow path */
5452 if ((s32)(tp->rx_opt.rcv_tsval - tp->rx_opt.ts_recent) < 0)
5453 goto slow_path;
5454
5455 /* DO NOT update ts_recent here, if checksum fails
5456 * and timestamp was corrupted part, it will result
5457 * in a hung connection since we will drop all
5458 * future packets due to the PAWS test.
5459 */
5460 }
5461
5462 if (len <= tcp_header_len) {
5463 /* Bulk data transfer: sender */
5464 if (len == tcp_header_len) {
5465 /* Predicted packet is in window by definition.
5466 * seq == rcv_nxt and rcv_wup <= rcv_nxt.
5467 * Hence, check seq<=rcv_wup reduces to:
5468 */
5469 if (tcp_header_len ==
5470 (sizeof(struct tcphdr) + TCPOLEN_TSTAMP_ALIGNED) &&
5471 tp->rcv_nxt == tp->rcv_wup)
5472 tcp_store_ts_recent(tp);
5473
5474 /* We know that such packets are checksummed
5475 * on entry.
5476 */
5477 tcp_ack(sk, skb, 0);
5478 __kfree_skb(skb);
5479 tcp_data_snd_check(sk);
5480 return;
5481 } else { /* Header too small */
5482 TCP_INC_STATS(sock_net(sk), TCP_MIB_INERRS);
5483 goto discard;
5484 }
5485 } else {
5486 int eaten = 0;
5487 bool fragstolen = false;
5488
5489 if (tcp_checksum_complete(skb))
5490 goto csum_error;
5491
5492 if ((int)skb->truesize > sk->sk_forward_alloc)
5493 goto step5;
5494
5495 /* Predicted packet is in window by definition.
5496 * seq == rcv_nxt and rcv_wup <= rcv_nxt.
5497 * Hence, check seq<=rcv_wup reduces to:
5498 */
5499 if (tcp_header_len ==
5500 (sizeof(struct tcphdr) + TCPOLEN_TSTAMP_ALIGNED) &&
5501 tp->rcv_nxt == tp->rcv_wup)
5502 tcp_store_ts_recent(tp);
5503
5504 tcp_rcv_rtt_measure_ts(sk, skb);
5505
5506 NET_INC_STATS(sock_net(sk), LINUX_MIB_TCPHPHITS);
5507
5508 /* Bulk data transfer: receiver */
5509 eaten = tcp_queue_rcv(sk, skb, tcp_header_len,
5510 &fragstolen);
5511
5512 tcp_event_data_recv(sk, skb);
5513
5514 if (TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->ack_seq != tp->snd_una) {
5515 /* Well, only one small jumplet in fast path... */
5516 tcp_ack(sk, skb, FLAG_DATA);
5517 tcp_data_snd_check(sk);
5518 if (!inet_csk_ack_scheduled(sk))
5519 goto no_ack;
5520 }
5521
5522 __tcp_ack_snd_check(sk, 0);
5523no_ack:
5524 if (eaten)
5525 kfree_skb_partial(skb, fragstolen);
5526 sk->sk_data_ready(sk);
5527 return;
5528 }
5529 }
5530
5531slow_path:
5532 if (len < (th->doff << 2) || tcp_checksum_complete(skb))
5533 goto csum_error;
5534
5535 if (!th->ack && !th->rst && !th->syn)
5536 goto discard;
5537
5538 /*
5539 * Standard slow path.
5540 */
5541
5542 if (!tcp_validate_incoming(sk, skb, th, 1))
5543 return;
5544
5545step5:
5546 if (tcp_ack(sk, skb, FLAG_SLOWPATH | FLAG_UPDATE_TS_RECENT) < 0)
5547 goto discard;
5548
5549 tcp_rcv_rtt_measure_ts(sk, skb);
5550
5551 /* Process urgent data. */
5552 tcp_urg(sk, skb, th);
5553
5554 /* step 7: process the segment text */
5555 tcp_data_queue(sk, skb);
5556
5557 tcp_data_snd_check(sk);
5558 tcp_ack_snd_check(sk);
5559 return;
5560
5561csum_error:
5562 TCP_INC_STATS(sock_net(sk), TCP_MIB_CSUMERRORS);
5563 TCP_INC_STATS(sock_net(sk), TCP_MIB_INERRS);
5564
5565discard:
5566 tcp_drop(sk, skb);
5567}
5568EXPORT_SYMBOL(tcp_rcv_established);
5569
5570void tcp_finish_connect(struct sock *sk, struct sk_buff *skb)
5571{
5572 struct tcp_sock *tp = tcp_sk(sk);
5573 struct inet_connection_sock *icsk = inet_csk(sk);
5574
5575 tcp_set_state(sk, TCP_ESTABLISHED);
5576 icsk->icsk_ack.lrcvtime = tcp_jiffies32;
5577
5578 if (skb) {
5579 icsk->icsk_af_ops->sk_rx_dst_set(sk, skb);
5580 security_inet_conn_established(sk, skb);
5581 }
5582
5583 /* Make sure socket is routed, for correct metrics. */
5584 icsk->icsk_af_ops->rebuild_header(sk);
5585
5586 tcp_init_metrics(sk);
5587 tcp_call_bpf(sk, BPF_SOCK_OPS_ACTIVE_ESTABLISHED_CB);
5588 tcp_init_congestion_control(sk);
5589
5590 /* Prevent spurious tcp_cwnd_restart() on first data
5591 * packet.
5592 */
5593 tp->lsndtime = tcp_jiffies32;
5594
5595 tcp_init_buffer_space(sk);
5596
5597 if (sock_flag(sk, SOCK_KEEPOPEN))
5598 inet_csk_reset_keepalive_timer(sk, keepalive_time_when(tp));
5599
5600 if (!tp->rx_opt.snd_wscale)
5601 __tcp_fast_path_on(tp, tp->snd_wnd);
5602 else
5603 tp->pred_flags = 0;
5604}
5605
5606static bool tcp_rcv_fastopen_synack(struct sock *sk, struct sk_buff *synack,
5607 struct tcp_fastopen_cookie *cookie)
5608{
5609 struct tcp_sock *tp = tcp_sk(sk);
5610 struct sk_buff *data = tp->syn_data ? tcp_write_queue_head(sk) : NULL;
5611 u16 mss = tp->rx_opt.mss_clamp, try_exp = 0;
5612 bool syn_drop = false;
5613
5614 if (mss == tp->rx_opt.user_mss) {
5615 struct tcp_options_received opt;
5616
5617 /* Get original SYNACK MSS value if user MSS sets mss_clamp */
5618 tcp_clear_options(&opt);
5619 opt.user_mss = opt.mss_clamp = 0;
5620 tcp_parse_options(sock_net(sk), synack, &opt, 0, NULL);
5621 mss = opt.mss_clamp;
5622 }
5623
5624 if (!tp->syn_fastopen) {
5625 /* Ignore an unsolicited cookie */
5626 cookie->len = -1;
5627 } else if (tp->total_retrans) {
5628 /* SYN timed out and the SYN-ACK neither has a cookie nor
5629 * acknowledges data. Presumably the remote received only
5630 * the retransmitted (regular) SYNs: either the original
5631 * SYN-data or the corresponding SYN-ACK was dropped.
5632 */
5633 syn_drop = (cookie->len < 0 && data);
5634 } else if (cookie->len < 0 && !tp->syn_data) {
5635 /* We requested a cookie but didn't get it. If we did not use
5636 * the (old) exp opt format then try so next time (try_exp=1).
5637 * Otherwise we go back to use the RFC7413 opt (try_exp=2).
5638 */
5639 try_exp = tp->syn_fastopen_exp ? 2 : 1;
5640 }
5641
5642 tcp_fastopen_cache_set(sk, mss, cookie, syn_drop, try_exp);
5643
5644 if (data) { /* Retransmit unacked data in SYN */
5645 tcp_for_write_queue_from(data, sk) {
5646 if (data == tcp_send_head(sk) ||
5647 __tcp_retransmit_skb(sk, data, 1))
5648 break;
5649 }
5650 tcp_rearm_rto(sk);
5651 NET_INC_STATS(sock_net(sk),
5652 LINUX_MIB_TCPFASTOPENACTIVEFAIL);
5653 return true;
5654 }
5655 tp->syn_data_acked = tp->syn_data;
5656 if (tp->syn_data_acked)
5657 NET_INC_STATS(sock_net(sk),
5658 LINUX_MIB_TCPFASTOPENACTIVE);
5659
5660 tcp_fastopen_add_skb(sk, synack);
5661
5662 return false;
5663}
5664
5665static int tcp_rcv_synsent_state_process(struct sock *sk, struct sk_buff *skb,
5666 const struct tcphdr *th)
5667{
5668 struct inet_connection_sock *icsk = inet_csk(sk);
5669 struct tcp_sock *tp = tcp_sk(sk);
5670 struct tcp_fastopen_cookie foc = { .len = -1 };
5671 int saved_clamp = tp->rx_opt.mss_clamp;
5672 bool fastopen_fail;
5673
5674 tcp_parse_options(sock_net(sk), skb, &tp->rx_opt, 0, &foc);
5675 if (tp->rx_opt.saw_tstamp && tp->rx_opt.rcv_tsecr)
5676 tp->rx_opt.rcv_tsecr -= tp->tsoffset;
5677
5678 if (th->ack) {
5679 /* rfc793:
5680 * "If the state is SYN-SENT then
5681 * first check the ACK bit
5682 * If the ACK bit is set
5683 * If SEG.ACK =< ISS, or SEG.ACK > SND.NXT, send
5684 * a reset (unless the RST bit is set, if so drop
5685 * the segment and return)"
5686 */
5687 if (!after(TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->ack_seq, tp->snd_una) ||
5688 after(TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->ack_seq, tp->snd_nxt))
5689 goto reset_and_undo;
5690
5691 if (tp->rx_opt.saw_tstamp && tp->rx_opt.rcv_tsecr &&
5692 !between(tp->rx_opt.rcv_tsecr, tp->retrans_stamp,
5693 tcp_time_stamp(tp))) {
5694 NET_INC_STATS(sock_net(sk),
5695 LINUX_MIB_PAWSACTIVEREJECTED);
5696 goto reset_and_undo;
5697 }
5698
5699 /* Now ACK is acceptable.
5700 *
5701 * "If the RST bit is set
5702 * If the ACK was acceptable then signal the user "error:
5703 * connection reset", drop the segment, enter CLOSED state,
5704 * delete TCB, and return."
5705 */
5706
5707 if (th->rst) {
5708 tcp_reset(sk);
5709 goto discard;
5710 }
5711
5712 /* rfc793:
5713 * "fifth, if neither of the SYN or RST bits is set then
5714 * drop the segment and return."
5715 *
5716 * See note below!
5717 * --ANK(990513)
5718 */
5719 if (!th->syn)
5720 goto discard_and_undo;
5721
5722 /* rfc793:
5723 * "If the SYN bit is on ...
5724 * are acceptable then ...
5725 * (our SYN has been ACKed), change the connection
5726 * state to ESTABLISHED..."
5727 */
5728
5729 tcp_ecn_rcv_synack(tp, th);
5730
5731 tcp_init_wl(tp, TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->seq);
5732 tcp_ack(sk, skb, FLAG_SLOWPATH);
5733
5734 /* Ok.. it's good. Set up sequence numbers and
5735 * move to established.
5736 */
5737 tp->rcv_nxt = TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->seq + 1;
5738 tp->rcv_wup = TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->seq + 1;
5739
5740 /* RFC1323: The window in SYN & SYN/ACK segments is
5741 * never scaled.
5742 */
5743 tp->snd_wnd = ntohs(th->window);
5744
5745 if (!tp->rx_opt.wscale_ok) {
5746 tp->rx_opt.snd_wscale = tp->rx_opt.rcv_wscale = 0;
5747 tp->window_clamp = min(tp->window_clamp, 65535U);
5748 }
5749
5750 if (tp->rx_opt.saw_tstamp) {
5751 tp->rx_opt.tstamp_ok = 1;
5752 tp->tcp_header_len =
5753 sizeof(struct tcphdr) + TCPOLEN_TSTAMP_ALIGNED;
5754 tp->advmss -= TCPOLEN_TSTAMP_ALIGNED;
5755 tcp_store_ts_recent(tp);
5756 } else {
5757 tp->tcp_header_len = sizeof(struct tcphdr);
5758 }
5759
5760 if (tcp_is_sack(tp) && sysctl_tcp_fack)
5761 tcp_enable_fack(tp);
5762
5763 tcp_mtup_init(sk);
5764 tcp_sync_mss(sk, icsk->icsk_pmtu_cookie);
5765 tcp_initialize_rcv_mss(sk);
5766
5767 /* Remember, tcp_poll() does not lock socket!
5768 * Change state from SYN-SENT only after copied_seq
5769 * is initialized. */
5770 tp->copied_seq = tp->rcv_nxt;
5771
5772 smp_mb();
5773
5774 tcp_finish_connect(sk, skb);
5775
5776 fastopen_fail = (tp->syn_fastopen || tp->syn_data) &&
5777 tcp_rcv_fastopen_synack(sk, skb, &foc);
5778
5779 if (!sock_flag(sk, SOCK_DEAD)) {
5780 sk->sk_state_change(sk);
5781 sk_wake_async(sk, SOCK_WAKE_IO, POLL_OUT);
5782 }
5783 if (fastopen_fail)
5784 return -1;
5785 if (sk->sk_write_pending ||
5786 icsk->icsk_accept_queue.rskq_defer_accept ||
5787 icsk->icsk_ack.pingpong) {
5788 /* Save one ACK. Data will be ready after
5789 * several ticks, if write_pending is set.
5790 *
5791 * It may be deleted, but with this feature tcpdumps
5792 * look so _wonderfully_ clever, that I was not able
5793 * to stand against the temptation 8) --ANK
5794 */
5795 inet_csk_schedule_ack(sk);
5796 tcp_enter_quickack_mode(sk);
5797 inet_csk_reset_xmit_timer(sk, ICSK_TIME_DACK,
5798 TCP_DELACK_MAX, TCP_RTO_MAX);
5799
5800discard:
5801 tcp_drop(sk, skb);
5802 return 0;
5803 } else {
5804 tcp_send_ack(sk);
5805 }
5806 return -1;
5807 }
5808
5809 /* No ACK in the segment */
5810
5811 if (th->rst) {
5812 /* rfc793:
5813 * "If the RST bit is set
5814 *
5815 * Otherwise (no ACK) drop the segment and return."
5816 */
5817
5818 goto discard_and_undo;
5819 }
5820
5821 /* PAWS check. */
5822 if (tp->rx_opt.ts_recent_stamp && tp->rx_opt.saw_tstamp &&
5823 tcp_paws_reject(&tp->rx_opt, 0))
5824 goto discard_and_undo;
5825
5826 if (th->syn) {
5827 /* We see SYN without ACK. It is attempt of
5828 * simultaneous connect with crossed SYNs.
5829 * Particularly, it can be connect to self.
5830 */
5831 tcp_set_state(sk, TCP_SYN_RECV);
5832
5833 if (tp->rx_opt.saw_tstamp) {
5834 tp->rx_opt.tstamp_ok = 1;
5835 tcp_store_ts_recent(tp);
5836 tp->tcp_header_len =
5837 sizeof(struct tcphdr) + TCPOLEN_TSTAMP_ALIGNED;
5838 } else {
5839 tp->tcp_header_len = sizeof(struct tcphdr);
5840 }
5841
5842 tp->rcv_nxt = TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->seq + 1;
5843 tp->copied_seq = tp->rcv_nxt;
5844 tp->rcv_wup = TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->seq + 1;
5845
5846 /* RFC1323: The window in SYN & SYN/ACK segments is
5847 * never scaled.
5848 */
5849 tp->snd_wnd = ntohs(th->window);
5850 tp->snd_wl1 = TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->seq;
5851 tp->max_window = tp->snd_wnd;
5852
5853 tcp_ecn_rcv_syn(tp, th);
5854
5855 tcp_mtup_init(sk);
5856 tcp_sync_mss(sk, icsk->icsk_pmtu_cookie);
5857 tcp_initialize_rcv_mss(sk);
5858
5859 tcp_send_synack(sk);
5860#if 0
5861 /* Note, we could accept data and URG from this segment.
5862 * There are no obstacles to make this (except that we must
5863 * either change tcp_recvmsg() to prevent it from returning data
5864 * before 3WHS completes per RFC793, or employ TCP Fast Open).
5865 *
5866 * However, if we ignore data in ACKless segments sometimes,
5867 * we have no reasons to accept it sometimes.
5868 * Also, seems the code doing it in step6 of tcp_rcv_state_process
5869 * is not flawless. So, discard packet for sanity.
5870 * Uncomment this return to process the data.
5871 */
5872 return -1;
5873#else
5874 goto discard;
5875#endif
5876 }
5877 /* "fifth, if neither of the SYN or RST bits is set then
5878 * drop the segment and return."
5879 */
5880
5881discard_and_undo:
5882 tcp_clear_options(&tp->rx_opt);
5883 tp->rx_opt.mss_clamp = saved_clamp;
5884 goto discard;
5885
5886reset_and_undo:
5887 tcp_clear_options(&tp->rx_opt);
5888 tp->rx_opt.mss_clamp = saved_clamp;
5889 return 1;
5890}
5891
5892/*
5893 * This function implements the receiving procedure of RFC 793 for
5894 * all states except ESTABLISHED and TIME_WAIT.
5895 * It's called from both tcp_v4_rcv and tcp_v6_rcv and should be
5896 * address independent.
5897 */
5898
5899int tcp_rcv_state_process(struct sock *sk, struct sk_buff *skb)
5900{
5901 struct tcp_sock *tp = tcp_sk(sk);
5902 struct inet_connection_sock *icsk = inet_csk(sk);
5903 const struct tcphdr *th = tcp_hdr(skb);
5904 struct request_sock *req;
5905 int queued = 0;
5906 bool acceptable;
5907
5908 switch (sk->sk_state) {
5909 case TCP_CLOSE:
5910 goto discard;
5911
5912 case TCP_LISTEN:
5913 if (th->ack)
5914 return 1;
5915
5916 if (th->rst)
5917 goto discard;
5918
5919 if (th->syn) {
5920 if (th->fin)
5921 goto discard;
5922 /* It is possible that we process SYN packets from backlog,
5923 * so we need to make sure to disable BH right there.
5924 */
5925 local_bh_disable();
5926 acceptable = icsk->icsk_af_ops->conn_request(sk, skb) >= 0;
5927 local_bh_enable();
5928
5929 if (!acceptable)
5930 return 1;
5931 consume_skb(skb);
5932 return 0;
5933 }
5934 goto discard;
5935
5936 case TCP_SYN_SENT:
5937 tp->rx_opt.saw_tstamp = 0;
5938 tcp_mstamp_refresh(tp);
5939 queued = tcp_rcv_synsent_state_process(sk, skb, th);
5940 if (queued >= 0)
5941 return queued;
5942
5943 /* Do step6 onward by hand. */
5944 tcp_urg(sk, skb, th);
5945 __kfree_skb(skb);
5946 tcp_data_snd_check(sk);
5947 return 0;
5948 }
5949
5950 tcp_mstamp_refresh(tp);
5951 tp->rx_opt.saw_tstamp = 0;
5952 req = tp->fastopen_rsk;
5953 if (req) {
5954 WARN_ON_ONCE(sk->sk_state != TCP_SYN_RECV &&
5955 sk->sk_state != TCP_FIN_WAIT1);
5956
5957 if (!tcp_check_req(sk, skb, req, true))
5958 goto discard;
5959 }
5960
5961 if (!th->ack && !th->rst && !th->syn)
5962 goto discard;
5963
5964 if (!tcp_validate_incoming(sk, skb, th, 0))
5965 return 0;
5966
5967 /* step 5: check the ACK field */
5968 acceptable = tcp_ack(sk, skb, FLAG_SLOWPATH |
5969 FLAG_UPDATE_TS_RECENT |
5970 FLAG_NO_CHALLENGE_ACK) > 0;
5971
5972 if (!acceptable) {
5973 if (sk->sk_state == TCP_SYN_RECV)
5974 return 1; /* send one RST */
5975 tcp_send_challenge_ack(sk, skb);
5976 goto discard;
5977 }
5978 switch (sk->sk_state) {
5979 case TCP_SYN_RECV:
5980 if (!tp->srtt_us)
5981 tcp_synack_rtt_meas(sk, req);
5982
5983 /* Once we leave TCP_SYN_RECV, we no longer need req
5984 * so release it.
5985 */
5986 if (req) {
5987 inet_csk(sk)->icsk_retransmits = 0;
5988 reqsk_fastopen_remove(sk, req, false);
5989 } else {
5990 /* Make sure socket is routed, for correct metrics. */
5991 icsk->icsk_af_ops->rebuild_header(sk);
5992 tcp_call_bpf(sk, BPF_SOCK_OPS_PASSIVE_ESTABLISHED_CB);
5993 tcp_init_congestion_control(sk);
5994
5995 tcp_mtup_init(sk);
5996 tp->copied_seq = tp->rcv_nxt;
5997 tcp_init_buffer_space(sk);
5998 }
5999 smp_mb();
6000 tcp_set_state(sk, TCP_ESTABLISHED);
6001 sk->sk_state_change(sk);
6002
6003 /* Note, that this wakeup is only for marginal crossed SYN case.
6004 * Passively open sockets are not waked up, because
6005 * sk->sk_sleep == NULL and sk->sk_socket == NULL.
6006 */
6007 if (sk->sk_socket)
6008 sk_wake_async(sk, SOCK_WAKE_IO, POLL_OUT);
6009
6010 tp->snd_una = TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->ack_seq;
6011 tp->snd_wnd = ntohs(th->window) << tp->rx_opt.snd_wscale;
6012 tcp_init_wl(tp, TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->seq);
6013
6014 if (tp->rx_opt.tstamp_ok)
6015 tp->advmss -= TCPOLEN_TSTAMP_ALIGNED;
6016
6017 if (req) {
6018 /* Re-arm the timer because data may have been sent out.
6019 * This is similar to the regular data transmission case
6020 * when new data has just been ack'ed.
6021 *
6022 * (TFO) - we could try to be more aggressive and
6023 * retransmitting any data sooner based on when they
6024 * are sent out.
6025 */
6026 tcp_rearm_rto(sk);
6027 } else
6028 tcp_init_metrics(sk);
6029
6030 if (!inet_csk(sk)->icsk_ca_ops->cong_control)
6031 tcp_update_pacing_rate(sk);
6032
6033 /* Prevent spurious tcp_cwnd_restart() on first data packet */
6034 tp->lsndtime = tcp_jiffies32;
6035
6036 tcp_initialize_rcv_mss(sk);
6037 tcp_fast_path_on(tp);
6038 break;
6039
6040 case TCP_FIN_WAIT1: {
6041 int tmo;
6042
6043 /* If we enter the TCP_FIN_WAIT1 state and we are a
6044 * Fast Open socket and this is the first acceptable
6045 * ACK we have received, this would have acknowledged
6046 * our SYNACK so stop the SYNACK timer.
6047 */
6048 if (req) {
6049 /* We no longer need the request sock. */
6050 reqsk_fastopen_remove(sk, req, false);
6051 tcp_rearm_rto(sk);
6052 }
6053 if (tp->snd_una != tp->write_seq)
6054 break;
6055
6056 tcp_set_state(sk, TCP_FIN_WAIT2);
6057 sk->sk_shutdown |= SEND_SHUTDOWN;
6058
6059 sk_dst_confirm(sk);
6060
6061 if (!sock_flag(sk, SOCK_DEAD)) {
6062 /* Wake up lingering close() */
6063 sk->sk_state_change(sk);
6064 break;
6065 }
6066
6067 if (tp->linger2 < 0) {
6068 tcp_done(sk);
6069 NET_INC_STATS(sock_net(sk), LINUX_MIB_TCPABORTONDATA);
6070 return 1;
6071 }
6072 if (TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->end_seq != TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->seq &&
6073 after(TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->end_seq - th->fin, tp->rcv_nxt)) {
6074 /* Receive out of order FIN after close() */
6075 if (tp->syn_fastopen && th->fin)
6076 tcp_fastopen_active_disable(sk);
6077 tcp_done(sk);
6078 NET_INC_STATS(sock_net(sk), LINUX_MIB_TCPABORTONDATA);
6079 return 1;
6080 }
6081
6082 tmo = tcp_fin_time(sk);
6083 if (tmo > TCP_TIMEWAIT_LEN) {
6084 inet_csk_reset_keepalive_timer(sk, tmo - TCP_TIMEWAIT_LEN);
6085 } else if (th->fin || sock_owned_by_user(sk)) {
6086 /* Bad case. We could lose such FIN otherwise.
6087 * It is not a big problem, but it looks confusing
6088 * and not so rare event. We still can lose it now,
6089 * if it spins in bh_lock_sock(), but it is really
6090 * marginal case.
6091 */
6092 inet_csk_reset_keepalive_timer(sk, tmo);
6093 } else {
6094 tcp_time_wait(sk, TCP_FIN_WAIT2, tmo);
6095 goto discard;
6096 }
6097 break;
6098 }
6099
6100 case TCP_CLOSING:
6101 if (tp->snd_una == tp->write_seq) {
6102 tcp_time_wait(sk, TCP_TIME_WAIT, 0);
6103 goto discard;
6104 }
6105 break;
6106
6107 case TCP_LAST_ACK:
6108 if (tp->snd_una == tp->write_seq) {
6109 tcp_update_metrics(sk);
6110 tcp_done(sk);
6111 goto discard;
6112 }
6113 break;
6114 }
6115
6116 /* step 6: check the URG bit */
6117 tcp_urg(sk, skb, th);
6118
6119 /* step 7: process the segment text */
6120 switch (sk->sk_state) {
6121 case TCP_CLOSE_WAIT:
6122 case TCP_CLOSING:
6123 case TCP_LAST_ACK:
6124 if (!before(TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->seq, tp->rcv_nxt))
6125 break;
6126 case TCP_FIN_WAIT1:
6127 case TCP_FIN_WAIT2:
6128 /* RFC 793 says to queue data in these states,
6129 * RFC 1122 says we MUST send a reset.
6130 * BSD 4.4 also does reset.
6131 */
6132 if (sk->sk_shutdown & RCV_SHUTDOWN) {
6133 if (TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->end_seq != TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->seq &&
6134 after(TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->end_seq - th->fin, tp->rcv_nxt)) {
6135 NET_INC_STATS(sock_net(sk), LINUX_MIB_TCPABORTONDATA);
6136 tcp_reset(sk);
6137 return 1;
6138 }
6139 }
6140 /* Fall through */
6141 case TCP_ESTABLISHED:
6142 tcp_data_queue(sk, skb);
6143 queued = 1;
6144 break;
6145 }
6146
6147 /* tcp_data could move socket to TIME-WAIT */
6148 if (sk->sk_state != TCP_CLOSE) {
6149 tcp_data_snd_check(sk);
6150 tcp_ack_snd_check(sk);
6151 }
6152
6153 if (!queued) {
6154discard:
6155 tcp_drop(sk, skb);
6156 }
6157 return 0;
6158}
6159EXPORT_SYMBOL(tcp_rcv_state_process);

6161static inline void pr_drop_req(struct request_sock *req, __u16 port, int family)
6162{
6163 struct inet_request_sock *ireq = inet_rsk(req);
6164
6165 if (family == AF_INET)
6166 net_dbg_ratelimited("drop open request from %pI4/%u\n",
6167 &ireq->ir_rmt_addr, port);
6168#if IS_ENABLED(CONFIG_IPV6)
6169 else if (family == AF_INET6)
6170 net_dbg_ratelimited("drop open request from %pI6/%u\n",
6171 &ireq->ir_v6_rmt_addr, port);
6172#endif
6173}
6174
6175/* RFC3168 : 6.1.1 SYN packets must not have ECT/ECN bits set
6176 *
6177 * If we receive a SYN packet with these bits set, it means a
6178 * network is playing bad games with TOS bits. In order to
6179 * avoid possible false congestion notifications, we disable
6180 * TCP ECN negotiation.
6181 *
6182 * Exception: tcp_ca wants ECN. This is required for DCTCP
6183 * congestion control: Linux DCTCP asserts ECT on all packets,
6184 * including SYN, which is most optimal solution; however,
6185 * others, such as FreeBSD do not.
6186 */
6187static void tcp_ecn_create_request(struct request_sock *req,
6188 const struct sk_buff *skb,
6189 const struct sock *listen_sk,
6190 const struct dst_entry *dst)
6191{
6192 const struct tcphdr *th = tcp_hdr(skb);
6193 const struct net *net = sock_net(listen_sk);
6194 bool th_ecn = th->ece && th->cwr;
6195 bool ect, ecn_ok;
6196 u32 ecn_ok_dst;
6197
6198 if (!th_ecn)
6199 return;
6200
6201 ect = !INET_ECN_is_not_ect(TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->ip_dsfield);
6202 ecn_ok_dst = dst_feature(dst, DST_FEATURE_ECN_MASK);
6203 ecn_ok = net->ipv4.sysctl_tcp_ecn || ecn_ok_dst;
6204
6205 if ((!ect && ecn_ok) || tcp_ca_needs_ecn(listen_sk) ||
6206 (ecn_ok_dst & DST_FEATURE_ECN_CA) ||
6207 tcp_bpf_ca_needs_ecn((struct sock *)req))
6208 inet_rsk(req)->ecn_ok = 1;
6209}

6211static void tcp_openreq_init(struct request_sock *req,
6212 const struct tcp_options_received *rx_opt,
6213 struct sk_buff *skb, const struct sock *sk)
6214{
6215 struct inet_request_sock *ireq = inet_rsk(req);
6216
6217 req->rsk_rcv_wnd = 0; /* So that tcp_send_synack() knows! */
6218 req->cookie_ts = 0;
6219 tcp_rsk(req)->rcv_isn = TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->seq;
6220 tcp_rsk(req)->rcv_nxt = TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->seq + 1;
6221 tcp_rsk(req)->snt_synack = tcp_clock_us();
6222 tcp_rsk(req)->last_oow_ack_time = 0;
6223 req->mss = rx_opt->mss_clamp;
6224 req->ts_recent = rx_opt->saw_tstamp ? rx_opt->rcv_tsval : 0;
6225 ireq->tstamp_ok = rx_opt->tstamp_ok;
6226 ireq->sack_ok = rx_opt->sack_ok;
6227 ireq->snd_wscale = rx_opt->snd_wscale;
6228 ireq->wscale_ok = rx_opt->wscale_ok;
6229 ireq->acked = 0;
6230 ireq->ecn_ok = 0;
6231 ireq->ir_rmt_port = tcp_hdr(skb)->source;
6232 ireq->ir_num = ntohs(tcp_hdr(skb)->dest);
6233 ireq->ir_mark = inet_request_mark(sk, skb);
6234}

6236struct request_sock *inet_reqsk_alloc(const struct request_sock_ops *ops,
6237 struct sock *sk_listener,
6238 bool attach_listener)
6239{
6240 struct request_sock *req = reqsk_alloc(ops, sk_listener,
6241 attach_listener);
6242
6243 if (req) {
6244 struct inet_request_sock *ireq = inet_rsk(req);
6245
6246 ireq->ireq_opt = NULL;
6247#if IS_ENABLED(CONFIG_IPV6)
6248 ireq->pktopts = NULL;
6249#endif
6250 atomic64_set(&ireq->ir_cookie, 0);
6251 ireq->ireq_state = TCP_NEW_SYN_RECV;
6252 write_pnet(&ireq->ireq_net, sock_net(sk_listener));
6253 ireq->ireq_family = sk_listener->sk_family;
6254 }
6255
6256 return req;
6257}

6260/*
6261 * Return true if a syncookie should be sent
6262 */
6263static bool tcp_syn_flood_action(const struct sock *sk,
6264 const struct sk_buff *skb,
6265 const char *proto)
6266{
6267 struct request_sock_queue *queue = &inet_csk(sk)->icsk_accept_queue;
6268 const char *msg = "Dropping request";
6269 bool want_cookie = false;
6270 struct net *net = sock_net(sk);
6271
6272#ifdef CONFIG_SYN_COOKIES
6273 if (net->ipv4.sysctl_tcp_syncookies) {
6274 msg = "Sending cookies";
6275 want_cookie = true;
6276 __NET_INC_STATS(sock_net(sk), LINUX_MIB_TCPREQQFULLDOCOOKIES);
6277 } else
6278#endif
6279 __NET_INC_STATS(sock_net(sk), LINUX_MIB_TCPREQQFULLDROP);
6280
6281 if (!queue->synflood_warned &&
6282 net->ipv4.sysctl_tcp_syncookies != 2 &&
6283 xchg(&queue->synflood_warned, 1) == 0)
6284 pr_info("%s: Possible SYN flooding on port %d. %s. Check SNMP counters.\n",
6285 proto, ntohs(tcp_hdr(skb)->dest), msg);
6286
6287 return want_cookie;
6288}

6290static void tcp_reqsk_record_syn(const struct sock *sk,
6291 struct request_sock *req,
6292 const struct sk_buff *skb)
6293{
6294 if (tcp_sk(sk)->save_syn) {
6295 u32 len = skb_network_header_len(skb) + tcp_hdrlen(skb);
6296 u32 *copy;
6297
6298 copy = kmalloc(len + sizeof(u32), GFP_ATOMIC);
6299 if (copy) {
6300 copy[0] = len;
6301 memcpy(&copy[1], skb_network_header(skb), len);
6302 req->saved_syn = copy;
6303 }
6304 }
6305}

6307int tcp_conn_request(struct request_sock_ops *rsk_ops,
6308 const struct tcp_request_sock_ops *af_ops,
6309 struct sock *sk, struct sk_buff *skb)
6310{
6311 struct tcp_fastopen_cookie foc = { .len = -1 };
6312 __u32 isn = TCP_SKB_CB(skb)->tcp_tw_isn;
6313 struct tcp_options_received tmp_opt;
6314 struct tcp_sock *tp = tcp_sk(sk);
6315 struct net *net = sock_net(sk);
6316 struct sock *fastopen_sk = NULL;
6317 struct request_sock *req;
6318 bool want_cookie = false;
6319 struct dst_entry *dst;
6320 struct flowi fl;
6321
6322 /* TW buckets are converted to open requests without
6323 * limitations, they conserve resources and peer is
6324 * evidently real one.
6325 */
6326 if ((net->ipv4.sysctl_tcp_syncookies == 2 ||
6327 inet_csk_reqsk_queue_is_full(sk)) && !isn) {
6328 want_cookie = tcp_syn_flood_action(sk, skb, rsk_ops->slab_name);
6329 if (!want_cookie)
6330 goto drop;
6331 }
6332
6333 if (sk_acceptq_is_full(sk)) {
6334 NET_INC_STATS(sock_net(sk), LINUX_MIB_LISTENOVERFLOWS);
6335 goto drop;
6336 }
6337
6338 req = inet_reqsk_alloc(rsk_ops, sk, !want_cookie);
6339 if (!req)
6340 goto drop;
6341
6342 tcp_rsk(req)->af_specific = af_ops;
6343 tcp_rsk(req)->ts_off = 0;
6344
6345 tcp_clear_options(&tmp_opt);
6346 tmp_opt.mss_clamp = af_ops->mss_clamp;
6347 tmp_opt.user_mss = tp->rx_opt.user_mss;
6348 tcp_parse_options(sock_net(sk), skb, &tmp_opt, 0,
6349 want_cookie ? NULL : &foc);
6350
6351 if (want_cookie && !tmp_opt.saw_tstamp)
6352 tcp_clear_options(&tmp_opt);
6353
6354 tmp_opt.tstamp_ok = tmp_opt.saw_tstamp;
6355 tcp_openreq_init(req, &tmp_opt, skb, sk);
6356 inet_rsk(req)->no_srccheck = inet_sk(sk)->transparent;
6357
6358 /* Note: tcp_v6_init_req() might override ir_iif for link locals */
6359 inet_rsk(req)->ir_iif = inet_request_bound_dev_if(sk, skb);
6360
6361 af_ops->init_req(req, sk, skb);
6362
6363 if (security_inet_conn_request(sk, skb, req))
6364 goto drop_and_free;
6365
6366 if (tmp_opt.tstamp_ok)
6367 tcp_rsk(req)->ts_off = af_ops->init_ts_off(net, skb);
6368
6369 dst = af_ops->route_req(sk, &fl, req);
6370 if (!dst)
6371 goto drop_and_free;
6372
6373 if (!want_cookie && !isn) {
6374 /* Kill the following clause, if you dislike this way. */
6375 if (!net->ipv4.sysctl_tcp_syncookies &&
6376 (net->ipv4.sysctl_max_syn_backlog - inet_csk_reqsk_queue_len(sk) <
6377 (net->ipv4.sysctl_max_syn_backlog >> 2)) &&
6378 !tcp_peer_is_proven(req, dst)) {
6379 /* Without syncookies last quarter of
6380 * backlog is filled with destinations,
6381 * proven to be alive.
6382 * It means that we continue to communicate
6383 * to destinations, already remembered
6384 * to the moment of synflood.
6385 */
6386 pr_drop_req(req, ntohs(tcp_hdr(skb)->source),
6387 rsk_ops->family);
6388 goto drop_and_release;
6389 }
6390
6391 isn = af_ops->init_seq(skb);
6392 }
6393
6394 tcp_ecn_create_request(req, skb, sk, dst);
6395
6396 if (want_cookie) {
6397 isn = cookie_init_sequence(af_ops, sk, skb, &req->mss);
6398 req->cookie_ts = tmp_opt.tstamp_ok;
6399 if (!tmp_opt.tstamp_ok)
6400 inet_rsk(req)->ecn_ok = 0;
6401 }
6402
6403 tcp_rsk(req)->snt_isn = isn;
6404 tcp_rsk(req)->txhash = net_tx_rndhash();
6405 tcp_openreq_init_rwin(req, sk, dst);
6406 if (!want_cookie) {
6407 tcp_reqsk_record_syn(sk, req, skb);
6408 fastopen_sk = tcp_try_fastopen(sk, skb, req, &foc);
6409 }
6410 if (fastopen_sk) {
6411 af_ops->send_synack(fastopen_sk, dst, &fl, req,
6412 &foc, TCP_SYNACK_FASTOPEN);
6413 /* Add the child socket directly into the accept queue */
6414 inet_csk_reqsk_queue_add(sk, req, fastopen_sk);
6415 sk->sk_data_ready(sk);
6416 bh_unlock_sock(fastopen_sk);
6417 sock_put(fastopen_sk);
6418 } else {
6419 tcp_rsk(req)->tfo_listener = false;
6420 if (!want_cookie)
6421 inet_csk_reqsk_queue_hash_add(sk, req,
6422 tcp_timeout_init((struct sock *)req));
6423 af_ops->send_synack(sk, dst, &fl, req, &foc,
6424 !want_cookie ? TCP_SYNACK_NORMAL :
6425 TCP_SYNACK_COOKIE);
6426 if (want_cookie) {
6427 reqsk_free(req);
6428 return 0;
6429 }
6430 }
6431 reqsk_put(req);
6432 return 0;
6433
6434drop_and_release:
6435 dst_release(dst);
6436drop_and_free:
6437 reqsk_free(req);
6438drop:
6439 tcp_listendrop(sk);
6440 return 0;
6441}
6442EXPORT_SYMBOL(tcp_conn_request);
